<div id="review_3022198758" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3022198758" />
    <a title="Cymru Roberts" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8997708-cymru-roberts"><img alt="Cymru Roberts" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606692362p2/8997708.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3022198758?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cymru Roberts" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cymru Roberts" href="/user/show/8997708-cymru-roberts">Cymru Roberts</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="paper 9780486406572" href="/book/show/753043.An_Enemy_of_the_People">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8997708-cymru-roberts?shelf=other-plays">other-plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8997708-cymru-roberts?shelf=henrik-ibsen">henrik-ibsen</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3022198758" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2401899474536010744">Ibsen offers the same kind of take on &quot;liberalism&quot; here that Henry James does is <i>Los Bostonians</i>––ie, that yes the establishment is fucked and corrupt, but the anti-establishment is just as bad, or at least as equally duplicitous. I hope that this is the message, in any event. Some of the notes taken from Ibsen&apos;s letters make it appear that Dr Stockmann was much more of a &quot;serious&quot; character than the caricature I took him to be, a kind of ingenious satire on the Commie kool-aid drinker. Regardles</span>
  <span id="freeText2401899474536010744" style="display:none">Ibsen offers the same kind of take on "liberalism" here that Henry James does is <i>Los Bostonians</i>––ie, that yes the establishment is fucked and corrupt, but the anti-establishment is just as bad, or at least as equally duplicitous. I hope that this is the message, in any event. Some of the notes taken from Ibsen's letters make it appear that Dr Stockmann was much more of a "serious" character than the caricature I took him to be, a kind of ingenious satire on the Commie kool-aid drinker. Regardless, when you refrain from taking sides to say both sides are equally bad––t'aint a popular view. "The strongest man on earth is he that is alone," is the ominous phrase utterred by Dr Stockmann to end the play, to the gleeful, somewhat insane sighs of his wife and daughter (whom he is about to disqualify from a lifetime of financial security). This has to be ironic, and yet if the lone woman who thinks for herself is the converse of "the masses" (see: the rabble, the horde, the 200K anonymous followers of take yer pic), then Ibsen might have a.... point? Does thinking for oneself, and espousing truth and justice, necessarily require that one go against "the majority"? I hope not, but I don't have much hope when it comes to such things. <br /><br />Ibsen deals with societal problems. I've come to believe that society can't be changed, but only individuals––and maybe <i>that's</i> even being naive, overly hopeful. I do read a lot of Sophocles, mind you. Whatever you believe––and I hope it's the result of thinking for yourself––be excellent to each other, and party on, dudes! :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2401899474536010744" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


