<div id="review_3762180179" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3762180179" />
    <a title="The Lazy Reader" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/96477815-the-lazy-reader"><img alt="The Lazy Reader" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556189018p2/96477815.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3762180179?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="The Lazy Reader" class="user" itemprop="url" name="The Lazy Reader" href="/user/show/96477815-the-lazy-reader">The Lazy Reader</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96477815-the-lazy-reader?shelf=audiobooks-dramas-lectures-podcasts">audiobooks-dramas-lectures-podcasts</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96477815-the-lazy-reader?shelf=x-nordic-dutch-belgian">x-nordic-dutch-belgian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96477815-the-lazy-reader?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96477815-the-lazy-reader?shelf=plays-and-theatre">plays-and-theatre</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96477815-the-lazy-reader?shelf=humor-parody">humor-parody</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3762180179" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8291647932182066853">A disillusioned, cynical treatise on the ideals of society worthy of Diogenes. Nothing is sacred, everything is torn down, mocked, spit on.The rule of democracy is a mob, the establishment is a farce. The masses are prejudiced, backward &quot;mutts&quot; led around by selfish, opportunist leaders willing to bargain their liberal, social reformer truths for a seat at the table. Some of this will ring painfully true. It is relevant because Ibsen serves human society some humble pie.<br/><br/>Mostly, he stands on a po</span>
  <span id="freeText8291647932182066853" style="display:none">A disillusioned, cynical treatise on the ideals of society worthy of Diogenes. Nothing is sacred, everything is torn down, mocked, spit on.The rule of democracy is a mob, the establishment is a farce. The masses are prejudiced, backward "mutts" led around by selfish, opportunist leaders willing to bargain their liberal, social reformer truths for a seat at the table. Some of this will ring painfully true. It is relevant because Ibsen serves human society some humble pie.<br /><br />Mostly, he stands on a podium and shouts "stupid, stupid, stupid!" down on a scandalized audience. This scene is literally the entirety of Act 4. A long, angry tirade about how nobody can appreciate his genius.<br /><br />But Diogenes understood what Ibsen didn't.You can't mock society, and then expect them to revere you too.<br /><br />His misanthropic beliefs, because what he criticises about societal values is society itself, would have been more enjoyable if he hadn't served it with a side load of arrogant certainty in his own beliefs.The people's truth is trash, but individualism is the real truth, those lone voices of reason, those philosopher kings terrorized by the ignorant, stupid masses. I wonder where Ibsen inherited this view from? Surely....not society? Not the very same thinkers born and brought up in community? No?<br /><br />Give this play to a zealot, bigot or a liberal, all will go away thinking pretty good about themselves. Ibsen is not the first one to think himself the most enlightened in the room or to write down his revenge fantasies.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8291647932182066853" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

